Lessons that can be learned from the Cuban Missile Crisis today
"Thirteen Days" ("Thirteen Days"), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is soon to be released in cinemas in numerous countries.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it provides insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors at the White House together.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a stationing for nuclear weapons in Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days in the White House.
Audio recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion panel intended to examine the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this panel included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a Harvard history professor who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard political science professor who thirty years ago presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision."
Additionally, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the film's treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the discussion participants agreed that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures that President Kennedy faced, as they actually were.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the case of a crisis, yet it is exclusively the president who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be pointed out that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; in addition, communication lines must remain open.
Pressing an opponent into a corner without maintaining diplomatic channels that allow for an understanding of the opponent's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, other allies, and the world's opinion had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into action.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were examined and weighed with the utmost care was crucial to the outcome.
But would such a period of time for deliberation still exist today, given the current mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the adversary's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy had imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, and not as a means to stop specific Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy was anxious about the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had for Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"The Berlin Crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban Missile Crisis," claimed the historian Ernest May.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely held argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the missiles – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
An 180,000-man-strong U.S. troop was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombardment that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those, 90 strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about this?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used."
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba burn to the ground, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!"
An invasion would therefore have possibly resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because Kennedy's government did not have sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often happens when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet nuclear attack on the United States.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: U-2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down despite explicit instructions from the chairman to the contrary.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis was known for his rational behavior, but rather someone of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be carried out in light of this terrible, yet entirely realistic, thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the Internet where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
